{"about 1144–":"omkring 1144–Afdød","1148–Female":"1148–Afdød","1170–Female":"1170–Afdød","1144–Male":"1144–Afdød","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"før 1170","about 1144":"omkring 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1144–":"circa 1144–Overleden","1148–Female":"1148–Overleden","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1144–Male":"1144–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"vóór 1170","about 1144":"circa 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"about 1144–":"about 1144–Deceased","1148–Female":"1148–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1144–Male":"1144–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"before 1170","about 1144":"about 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chevaler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Patrice, Serge, Gabrielle, Jacques, Marcel, Michel, Raoul, Sylvain, Adelore, Antoine.","French: from Old French <i>chevalier</i> ‘knight’ (literally ‘horseman, rider’, from Late Latin <i>caballarius</i>, a derivative of <i>caballus</i> ‘horse’). In the Middle Ages only men of comparative wealth were able to afford the upkeep of a riding horse. It is likely that in the majority of cases the surname was originally a nickname, or an occupational name for a knight's servant, rather than a status name, for most men of the knightly class belonged to noble families which had more specific surnames derived from their estates. This was a name of Norman origin in England but probably did not survive the medieval period, and was later reintroduced by Huguenot refugees.","History: Joseph Chevalier from Dieppe in Seine-Maritime, France, married Françoise-Marthe Barton in Montreal, QC, in 1670. Pierre Chevalier <i>dit</i> Labbé and Duchesne from Pont-l'Abbé-d'Arnoult in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie-Madeleine Ménard in Montreal, QC, in 1697. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Alexis Dulignon <i>dit</i> Chevalier (a descendant of Jean Dulignon from La Rochefoucaud in Charente, France), who married Judith (de) Billy in Louiseville, QC, in 1778. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavalier","meanings":["French (southern): variant of   Chevalier   ‘knight, rider’. This surname is also found in Britain, where it is of Huguenot origin.","History: André Cavalier from Bordeaux in Gironde, France, married first Isabelle-Barbe Brousillon in New Orleans, LA, <i>c.</i> 1760, and second Marie-Jeanne Le Cossec/Cosse in New Orleans in 1770."]},{"name":"Chevallier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Blanchard, Christophe, Francois.","French: variant of   Chevalier   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":71,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":80,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":115,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William de Chevaler was born about 1144, in Northamptonshire, England. He married Tolleshunt of Essex before 1170, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1144–":"umbes 1144–Surnud","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1144–Male":"1144–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"enne 1170","about 1144":"umbes 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1144–":"noin 1144–Kuollut","1148–Female":"1148–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1144–Male":"1144–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"ennen vuotta 1170","about 1144":"noin 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1144–":"environ 1144–Décédé","1148–Female":"1148–Décédée","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1144–Male":"1144–Décédé","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","before 1170":"avant 1170","about 1144":"environ 1144","1170":"1170","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Chevaler est né environ 1144, à Northamptonshire, Angleterre. Il a épousé Tolleshunt of Essex avant 1170, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1144–":"um 1144–Verstorben","1148–Female":"1148–Verstorben","1170–Female":"1170–Verstorben","1144–Male":"1144–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215"